question_category.info: The default category for questions shared in context 'WS111-MS-DE'.

question.questiontext: The first page that is displayed is after logging into the eLearning system is the

answer.feedback: The My Courses Page shows a list of all classes that you are enrolled in. Active classes will be displayed in bold purple text. Classes from the previous semester will be displayed in gray text.

question.questiontext: If you need help immediately and can't wait for a support ticket reply, are there any self-help options?

answer.answertext: You will just have to be patient until someone gets back to you.
Just start clicking buttons and see what happens.

question.questiontext: To take attendance for your class, click on the Attendance link from the
To organize your workspace so it requires less scrolling and fewer clicks to complete tasks, it is recommended to move the following items to the left sidebar (check all that apply):

answer.feedback: Moving these items to the left sidebar is not required, but I do find that it makes navigating the site much more efficient. You are welcome to customize the page any way you like and move any other feature blocks to the left sidebar as well. Go ahead! Have fun with it!

question.questiontext: True or False: The eLearning Calendar can be accessed from the My Courses Page AND the Course Home Page.
True or False: Messages can be accessed from the My Courses Page AND the Course Home Page.
Breadcrumbs on a website

answer.answertext: show your location within the hierarchy of pages in the website.
lead you out of the virtual forest.
are generally located in the page footer.

question.questiontext:
(Choose the best answer.)

To navigate back to the Course Home Page from the Attendance module, click on

answer.answertext: the course code (ie: PSY101-DE.S13-SD) link in the breadcrumbs at the top of the page.
the Pacific College of Oriental Medicine logo.
the Home link in the breadcrumbs at the top of the page.
the button at the top right corner of the page with your name on it.

question.questiontext: What links would you click to request help from the IT Department and/or the eLearning Development Team?

answer.answertext: eLearning Support in the Support Block

question.questiontext: Before the new semester of classes start, what task must instructors complete in the Pacific College eLearning system:

answer.answertext: Setup class sessions (date and times of class meetings)
answer.feedback: This sets up your class so that you can take attendance for each class meeting. If sessions are not set up in the eLearning system, it will appear (from the Attendance Monitor's perspective) as if your class does not meet at all.

answer.answertext: Enroll each student manually into their class
Load all their class content into the eLearning interface
Nothing, the class is automatically ready to go on the first day of class.

question.questiontext: To add new sessions for attendance, open the Attendance module then click on the ________ tab along the top of the page.
If a class meets more than one time during the course of the semester, what option must be selected when setting up class sessions for attendance?

answer.feedback: This method is much easier and more convient then creating each session one by one.

answer.answertext: Session date and session end date fields

question.questiontext: To take attendance for a class, in the Attendance module, click on the

answer.answertext: The green dot next to the session for the current date

question.questiontext: After you have entered the status of each student in your class in the attendance module (ie: present, late, absent), what is the final step?

answer.answertext: Click the Save Attendance button at the bottom of the page.
answer.feedback: If you dont click save then it will be like no changes were ever made.

answer.answertext: Click on the course title in the breadcrumbs to return to the Course Home Page.
Click on the PCOM logo at the top of the page to return to the home page.

question.questiontext: The purpose of the shared files folder is...

answer.answertext: To provide a place to store handouts, presentations, files, and other documents that can be shared with the entire class
To chat and share stories with the class

question.questiontext: To add your course syllabus, you must ______________ and select File from the ________________ menu.

answer.answertext: turn editing on | Add an activity or resource
answer.feedback: Or you can drag and drop your syllabus from your files to the Welcome block on the Course Homepage.

answer.answertext: return to the home page | New resource
wish upon a star | Magic course builder

question.questiontext: The course syllabus must be _______ before it can be uploaded to the Pacific College eLearning system.

answer.answertext: the same syllabus that was used the previous semester,

question.questiontext: True or False: You must first click the Turn editing on button before you can drag and drop your course syllabus onto the Course Home Page.

answer.feedback: If you're confused because the editing tools aren't there, just remember, turn editing on!

question.questiontext:
True or False: A PDF is the recomended file type to use when uploading a file to the "Shared
Files" folder.

answer.feedback: We use PDF instead of Microsoft Word or PowerPoint because PDF is a free software that a student can upload to able to view these documents, whereas it is not required to have Microsoft Word or Microsoft PowerPoint software to be a student here at Pacific College.

question.questiontext: What path would you follow to add a picture and a brief description about yourself in your online profile?

answer.feedback: Once on the Edit profile page, you can click the information icon for more details on the required format and size of the picture you add.

question.questiontext: True or False: Any photos or descriptions added to the Pacific College eLearning online profile page are public, must be on a professional level, and must adhere to the Pacific College of Oriental Medicine policy regarding acceptable use of electronic communications.

answer.feedback: Of course, I am sure that this won't ever be a problem, but Human Resources requires that I mention it.

question.questiontext: True or False: Sending an Announcement message displays the message in the Announcements module and emails the message to all students enrolled in the course.

answer.feedback: The Announcements feature of the eLearning system is a great way to communicate with your students about upcoming events in the class. It also keeps an ongoing log of all messages sent, just click on the Announcements link to view all of the messages you've sent throughout the semester.

question.questiontext: True or False: Attachments such as the course syllabus or a handout can be added to an Announcement and sent to the entire class.

answer.feedback: This is an easy way to send a document to the entire class in one step. Alternatively, handouts or other documents can also be loaded to the Shared Files folder so students can access them at any time.

question.questiontext:
The Messages feature in Pacific College eLearning can be used to:

(check all that apply)

answer.answertext: Communicate back and forth with individual students in the class
Build a contact list of frequently used contacts to make communication easier.
Provide a convenient link between students and instructors
Broadcast mass communications to the entire class
answer.feedback: The messages feature is not really intended for mass communications, it is better suited for individual communications. To send a message to all the students in your class at once, use the Announcements feature.

question.questiontext: To see a list of all students and instructors enrolled in a class, click on the ______________ link from the Course Home Page.

answer.feedback: You can also see a list of students on the Attendance page, but this is a little quicker with fewer clicks, and you can send messages directly to individual students from the Participants page.

question.questiontext: True or False: You can access your messages from almost any page on the eLearning website.

answer.feedback: From the My Courses page, click on the word Messages in the Messages block. From the Course Home Page, click on Participants link to view a list of all students in the class to send messages to. From any page, you can also click on the exclamation mark button at the top, near your name to review any alerts and notifications of new messages received.

question.questiontext: When adding a user picture to your profile, what type of files or image formats are you able to use? (check all that apply)

answer.feedback: On the Edit profile page, you can also click the information icon to view the details about the format and size requirements for pictures.

question.questiontext: When you send an annoucement through the eLearning system, students recieve the message in the following ways? (check all that apply)

answer.answertext: the message is displayed in the Annoucements forum
answer.feedback: The Announcements forum is essentially an ongoing log of messages sent throughout the semester.

answer.answertext: an email is sent to each students Pacific College email address
each students spidey sense begins to tingle

question.questiontext: Removing a message from the Alerts and Notifications area completely deletes the message.

answer.feedback: Removing a message from your Alerts will only remove the alert notification. You can still view the message in your unread messages list. Messages are never completely deleted.

question_category.info: The default category for questions shared in context 'Quiz 3'.

question.name: Q1
question.questiontext: Which of the following is true regarding basic science research?

answer.answertext: Can generally be applied directly to patients in practice.
Is always based on the study of human populations.
Is usually preliminary in nature, leading to additional research.
Is always based on research done with test tubes and petri dishes.

question.name: Q2
question.questiontext: In 1998, a British medical doctor published a paper describing a case series of 12 children who were consecutively referred to a pediatric department with a history of developmental disorders and intestinal complaints. Of these, eight children were documented as having symptoms of autism which appeared within one month of receiving the measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccine. (Wakefield 1998) Which one of the following is true?

answer.answertext: This study proves that MMR vaccines cause autism in British children.
This case series does not establish causality between MMR vaccination and onset of autism.
This study used randomization to limit bias.

question.name: Q3
question.questiontext: Researchers prospectively evaluated the association between green tea consumption and colorectal cancer risk in a cohort of 69,710 Chinese women aged 40 to 70 years. Which of the following statements are true about this study?

answer.answertext: It is an example of a case controlled trial.
The exposure of interest is green tea consumption.
The study will tell us if green tea causes colorectal cancer.
The study design makes bias very unlikely.

question.name: Q4
question.questiontext: Which of the following questions would best be answered by quantitative research?

answer.answertext: When patients say they are satisfied with treatment, what do they mean?
What percentage of patients in the campus clinic are satisfied with the care they receive?
How would patients describe a satisfactory treatment?
What factors do patients consider when they rate their satisfaction?

question.name: Q5
question.questiontext: Which of the following is true regarding the evidence pyramid (hierarchy of evidence)?

answer.answertext: The pyramid reflects a relative ranking of research evidence, with the most valid types of evidence forming the base.
The pyramid suggests that randomized controlled trials are the first place to look to answer clinical questions.
A strength of the pyramid is that it includes research evidence that can be used to answer every type of clinical question.
The pyramid suggests that summary research is the best place to find information about effective treatment.

question.name: Q6
question.questiontext: Jane is 37 years old and has degenerative hip disease. Jane asks her physician whether acupuncture is effective at decreasing hip pain associated with osteoarthritis. The evidence pyramid (hierarchy of evidence) would help guide Janes physician to:

answer.answertext: First look for individual research articles regarding effectiveness.
First look for summary resources regarding effectiveness.
First look for qualitative research regarding patient satisfaction.
First look for observational studies regarding prognosis.

question.name: Q7
question.questiontext:
A study published in 2005 compared the Atkins, Ornish, Weight Watchers, and Zone diets for weight loss and heart disease risk reduction (Dansinger et al). The association of weight loss with diet had a p-value of .40; the association of weight loss with dietary adherence had a p-value of <.001. The power of the study was 85%.

Which association was found to be statistically significant?

question.name: Q8
question.questiontext: A research paper gave a detailed report of a woman with severe multiple sclerosis whose symptoms were relieved by massage therapy. This is an example of which type of study?

question.name: Q9
question.questiontext: You are reading a randomized controlled trial, which compared acupuncture to physical therapy for the treatment of neck pain. The study appears to be well done, but you cannot determine what selection criteria was used to select participants. Which one of the following statements is true?

answer.answertext: The selection criteria are unimportant since the study was randomized.
Most studies do not describe selection criteria.
The study lacks a placebo, and is therefore not useful.

question.name: Q10
question.questiontext: Which one of the statements regarding observational studies is true?

answer.answertext: Due to their design they are relatively free of bias.
They are well suited to determine treatment effectiveness.

question.name: Q11
question.questiontext: Which of the following is the most useful resource (according to the usefulness equation) for determining if an ergonomic assessment of a patients workspace is likely to improve her condition?

answer.answertext: A practice management article written in a trade magazine.
A case series on ergonomic interventions for office workers published in Spine journal.
A systematic review of ergonomic interventions found in the Cochrane Library.
A randomized controlled trial found in the PubMed database.

question.name: Q12
question.questiontext:
Use the following scenario to answer the following question:

Your patient has a family history of both heart disease and alcoholism. She read that red wine is good for cardiovascular health and asks you if she should start drinking a glass of wine each day. A search of wine and cardiovascular disease in a research database (Cochrane Library) quickly brings up several summary review articles, all of which agree that moderate consumption of red wine appears beneficial in preventing heart disease.

Given this scenario, how useful is the information from the review articles?

answer.answertext: Relevant and valid, but too much work
Relevant and valid and not too much work

question.name: Q13
question.questiontext:
Use the following scenario to answer the following question:

Your patient has a family history of both heart disease and alcoholism. She read that red wine is good for cardiovascular health and asks you if she should start drinking a glass of wine each day. A search of wine and cardiovascular disease in a research database (Cochrane Library) quickly brings up several summary review articles, all of which agree that moderate consumption of red wine appears beneficial in preventing heart disease.

Given this scenario, which option below is an evidenced informed practice approach?

answer.answertext: The research implies it is safe for this patient to begin drinking red wine daily.
Considering her family history, this patient should consider options other than drinking red wine to prevent heart disease.
Drinking red wine does not help prevent heart disease.
The research is not relevant to this case.

question.name: Q14
question.questiontext: Which of the following is a limitation of using textbooks?

answer.answertext: They are often a mixture of opinion and fact.
They generally include an index of hallmark references.

question.name: Q15
question.questiontext: Which of the following is a poor way for practitioners to keep up-to-date with new research in their field?

answer.answertext: Regularly scanning the Table of Contents in key journals relevant to ones field.

question.name: Q16
question.questiontext:
A study investigated whether children with ear infections improve after chiropractic treatment. When you read the study you find that participants, ranging in ages from 5-10, indicated their degree of pain using an age-appropriate instrument. Independent observers also conducted an otoscopic exam of the childrens ears before and after treatment.

Based on the scenario above, which one of the following is true?

answer.answertext: The study design will likely exaggerate the effectiveness of spinal manipulation.
The study may be relevant to children you are treating for ear infections.
To limit bias, patients older than 10 years should have been included.
The outcomes measured in the study will lead to biased results.

question.name: Q17
question.questiontext:
A study investigated the effects of massage therapy on cervical range of motion. Cervical range of motion was assessed by the treating therapist before the first treatment, at week 6, and after the last day of treatment at week 12.

Based on this description which is true regarding the study?

answer.answertext: Assuming appropriate randomization the researchers effectively limited bias.
The study design is prone to bias.
Cervical range of motion should not have been assessed at week 6.
Cervical range of motion should not have been assessed before the first treatment.

question.name: Q18
question.questiontext:
A study compared massage therapy and exercise for the treatment of low back pain. Patients were selected based on pain severity, frequency, and duration. Patients who failed exercise treatment in the past were enrolled in the massage therapy treatment arm.

Based on this description which statement below is true?

answer.answertext: The researchers should not have considered pain severity when selecting participants.
The massage therapy arm of the study is random, but the exercise arm is not.
The study may exaggerate the effectiveness of exercise therapy.
The results of the study are likely valid.

question.name: Q19
question.questiontext:
A study comparing a group that received acupuncture treatments for low back pain to a control group that received no treatment had a power of 85%.

Which of the following statements best describes what that means?

answer.answertext: If the acupuncture treatment is effective for low back pain, the p-value will be 0.85.
The study will have statistically significant results.
If there really is a difference of outcome between acupuncture treatment and the control group, there are enough study participants to find it.

question.name: Q20
question.questiontext: If the relative risk between two treatments is 1.4, then:

answer.answertext: The likelihood of something happening is 40% higher due to one treatment than the other.
The likelihood of something happening is 4 times higher due to one treatment than the other.
The likelihood of something happening is 1 in 4.

question.name: Q21
question.questiontext: Which one of the following best describes confidence intervals?

answer.answertext: Takes into account that some people will benefit even without therapy.
The ability of a study to find a difference between groups if the difference really exists.
Compares the probability of either harm or benefit of one treatment as compared with another.
Help us to understand how close our statistical estimate is to the truth.

question.name: Q22
question.questiontext:
Researchers conduct a randomized controlled trial comparing laparoscopic surgery to traditional surgery. Each time a subject was found eligible to participate in the study, a research assistant assigned that patient to either the laparoscopic or traditional surgery group by opening a sealed, opaque envelope and reading the card inside. The envelopes were prepared by a statistician before the study started, and the research assistant did not know which assignment was in any of the envelopes.

Is this an example of concealed allocation? Why or why not?

answer.answertext: No, because the statistician has influenced treatment assignment.
Yes, because the research assistant cannot influence the treatment assignment.
No, because the treatment assignment is not random.
Yes, because the study is a randomized controlled trial.

question.name: Q23
question.questiontext: Which one of the following is true of randomized clinical trials?

answer.answertext: The treatment provider must be blinded to the treatment they are providing.
They may use blinding to help limit bias.
The results of randomized controlled trials are readily generalizable to individual patients.

question.name: Q24
question.questiontext:
Consider the following scenario:

A research assistant assigns patients to treatment groups in an exercise study as follows: Patients who come to the clinic on Mondays receive instruction in strengthening exercises. Patients who come to the clinic on Wednesdays receive instruction in stretching exercises.

Which one of the following statements is true?

answer.answertext: This is an example of concealed allocation.
The process is unlikely to affect the outcomes of the study.
The process is random as long as the research assistant consistently does it the same way.

question.name: Q25
question.questiontext: Which one of the statements is true regarding meta-analyses?

answer.answertext: They use systematic search strategies to locate original studies.
They do not critically appraise original studies.
They provide a qualitative synthesis of studies.

question.name: Q26
question.questiontext:
A clinician is writing an article summarizing the research literature on neck pain after motor vehicle accidents. She identifies several articles, includes only those that demonstrate that motor vehicle accidents result in long-term disability. The included studies are not evaluated for validity.

What type of summary research is the clinician conducting?

question.name: Q27
question.questiontext: Which of the following is true?

answer.answertext: Randomization ensures that all patients end up in the treatment group that will benefit them the most.
P-values help researchers determine how many patients to include in a study.
Systematic reviews critically appraise the original research they include.

question.name: Q28
question.questiontext: Which one of the following is an important question to ask when you are assessing the relevance of a randomized controlled trial?

answer.answertext: Did the researchers search strategy lead them to find all of the relevant studies?
Will the information, if true, influence the way I practice?
Was follow up data collected for at least 80% of study participants?

question.name: Q29
question.questiontext: You are treating a patient with knee pain due to osteoarthritis. She asks you if she should take glucosamine to help manage her knee pain. Which one of the following is the most efficient strategy to answer your patients question?

answer.answertext: Conduct a search for randomized controlled trials using the search term: glucosamine.
Conduct a search for systematic reviews using the search terms: glucosamine and knee osteoarthritis.
Conduct a search for case reports of patients with knee osteoarthritis.
Conduct a search for randomized controlled trials using the search terms: glucosamine and knee osteoarthritis.

question.name: Q30
question.questiontext: Based on the study results, which of the following is true? (use abstract provided)

answer.answertext: In the short term (after 8 weeks), back-related dysfunction was better for those who received standardized acupuncture compared to simulated acupuncture.
In the short term (after 8 weeks), there was no clinically meaningful difference between groups in terms of improvement.
In the long term (after 1 year), back-related dysfunction in participants receiving usual care did not improve as much as in those who received acupuncture.
In the long term (after 1 year), symptoms were significantly less for those who received acupuncture, compared to usual care.

question.name: Q31
question.questiontext: Which of these indicators of study validity is true in this study? (use abstract provided)

answer.answertext: Outcome measures were collected in a way such that researchers could influence the results.
Study participants were not randomly assigned to treatment.

question.name: Q32
question.questiontext: This study is an example of which one of the following? (use abstract provided)
